CountryData

CountryData$Population = c(199000,1390000,1240000,7997,318000)
CountryData

Country = c("Australia","Greece")
LifeExpectancy = c(82,81)
Population = c(23050,11125)

NewCountryData = data.frame(Country, LifeExpectancy, Population)

#Combine CountryData and NewCountryData
AllCountryData = rbind(CountryData, NewCountryData)

2. Branch and Loop in R¶

2.1. If...else... statement¶

In [15]:
x <- -5
if(x >= 0){
  print("Non-negative number")
} else {
  print("Negative number")
}

[1] "Negative number"

2.2. If...else... ladder¶

In [16]:
x <- 0
if (x < 0) {
  print("Negative number")
} else if (x > 0) {
  print("Positive number")
} else
print("Zero")

[1] "Zero"

2.3. For loop¶

In [17]:
#Count the number of odd numbers

x <- c(2,5,3,9,8,11,6)
count <- 0
for (val in x) {
  if(val %% 2 == 1)  count = count+1
}
print(count)

[1] 4

2.4. While loop¶

In [18]:
i <- 1
while (i < 6) {
  print(i)
  i = i+1
}

[1] 1
[1] 2
[1] 3
[1] 4
[1] 5

3. Define your own functions in R¶

In [19]:
## Define a power function on your own
pow <- function(x, y) {
 result <- x^y
  print(paste(x,"raised to the power of", y, "is", result))
  return(result) 
}

a = 2
b = 10
r = pow(a,b)
print(r)

[1] "2 raised to the power of 10 is 1024"
[1] 1024

match("CAVIAR", USDA$Description)

4.9. Find amount of sodium in caviar¶

In [29]:
USDA$Sodium[match("CAVIAR", USDA$Description)]
1500

In [32]:
plot(USDA$Protein, USDA$TotalFat)

Adding xlabel, ylabel and title¶

In [33]:
plot(USDA$Protein, USDA$TotalFat, xlab="Protein", ylab = "Fat", main = "Protein vs Fat", col = "red")

4.13. Creating a histogram¶

In [34]:
hist(USDA$VitaminC, xlab = "Vitamin C (mg)", main = "Histogram of Vitamin C")

Add limits to x-axis¶

In [35]:
hist(USDA$VitaminC, xlab = "Vitamin C (mg)", main = "Histogram of Vitamin C", xlim = c(0,100))

Specifying breaks of histogram¶

In [36]:
hist(USDA$VitaminC, xlab = "Vitamin C (mg)", main = "Histogram of Vitamin C", xlim = c(0,100), breaks=100)
  hist(USDA$VitaminC, xlab = "Vitamin C (mg)", main = "Histogram of Vitamin C", xlim = c(0,100), breaks=2000)

4.14. Boxplots¶

In [37]:
boxplot(USDA$Sugar, ylab = "Sugar (g)", main = "Boxplot of Sugar")

4.15. Creating a variable that takes value 1 if the food has higher sodium than average, 0 otherwise¶

In [38]:
HighSodium = as.numeric(USDA$Sodium > mean(USDA$Sodium, na.rm=TRUE))
  str(HighSodium)

 num [1:7058] 1 1 0 1 1 1 1 1 1 1 ...

Adding the variable to the USDA data frame¶

In [39]:
USDA$HighSodium = as.numeric(USDA$Sodium > mean(USDA$Sodium, na.rm=TRUE))

Similarly for HighProtein, HigCarbs, HighFat¶

In [40]:
USDA$HighCarbs = as.numeric(USDA$Carbohydrate > mean(USDA$Carbohydrate, na.rm=TRUE))
  USDA$HighProtein = as.numeric(USDA$Protein > mean(USDA$Protein, na.rm=TRUE))
  USDA$HighFat = as.numeric(USDA$TotalFat > mean(USDA$TotalFat, na.rm=TRUE))
